My previous attempt to fix the issue was unsuccessful. The crash remains the same, indicating my change did not address the root cause. I need to re-analyze the problem.

The core issue is that a `getelementptr` instruction (`%p.4`) is being incorrectly classified as "scalar" when it should be "widened" (vectorized). This GEP is used by a `load` instruction that will be vectorized, and it's also used outside the loop as a return value. The use outside the loop seems to be what's confusing the cost model into thinking the GEP should be scalar.

My previous fix attempted to modify the logic in `collectLoopScalars` to ignore uses outside the loop. This was incorrect because that logic propagates scalar properties backwards from users to operands. The GEP itself is the one that needs to be classified correctly first.

The decision to widen or scalarize happens in `VPRecipeBuilder::tryToCreateWidenRecipe`, which calls `VPRecipeBuilder::shouldWiden`. `shouldWiden` in turn calls `LoopVectorizationCostModel::isScalarAfterVectorization`. This function is the key. It returns `true` if an instruction is in the `Scalars` set for the current vectorization factor.

The `Scalars` set is populated in `collectLoopScalars`. I need to find how `%p.4` gets into this set.
After re-examining `collectLoopScalars`, I've found a different worklist expansion loop that seems to be the culprit:

```cpp
// In LoopVectorize.cpp, inside collectLoopScalars
unsigned Idx = 0;
while (Idx != Worklist.size()) {
  Instruction *Dst = Worklist[Idx++];
  if (!IsLoopVaryingGEP(Dst->getOperand(0)))
    continue;
  auto *Src = cast<Instruction>(Dst->getOperand(0));
  if (llvm::all_of(Src->users(), [&](User *U) -> bool {
        auto *J = cast<Instruction>(U);
        return !TheLoop->contains(J) || Worklist.count(J) ||
               ((isa<LoadInst>(J) || isa<StoreInst>(J)) &&
                IsScalarUse(J, Src));
      })) {
    Worklist.insert(Src);
  }
}
```
This loop propagates the scalar property from an instruction `Dst` to its operand `Src`. The condition `!TheLoop->contains(J)` allows a user outside the loop to be considered "scalar", which contributes to the `all_of` being true. If an instruction's only non-scalar use is outside the loop, this logic will incorrectly classify it as scalar.

This is exactly the case for the GEP `%p.4`. Its user `ret` is outside the loop. Its other user, the `load`, is vectorized, so `IsScalarUse` is false for it. However, if the analysis starts from a different point and `%p.4`'s operand (`%ptr.iv`) is being considered, the logic can fail.

The most direct way to fix this is to prevent the use outside the loop from influencing the decision. I will remove the `!TheLoop->contains(J) ||` part of the condition. This forces the decision to be based only on in-loop users. If an instruction has a vector use inside the loop, it will not be marked as scalar, which is the correct behavior. The live-out value for the external user will be correctly extracted from the vectorized value later.

This is the same reasoning as my previous attempt, but I believe I targeted the wrong loop. There are multiple similar worklist expansion loops. The one at line 3175 is the one that seems to apply to GEP operands.

